INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1580','letter','1787-09-30','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Madison','Sr','individual','','I arrived here on monday last. The act of the Convention was then before Congress. It has been since taken up, and by a unanimous vote forwarded to the States, to be proceeded on as recommended by the Convention.','ltr_mad1580.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1581','letter','1787-10-14','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','No decisive indications of the public mind in the Northern and middle States can yet be collected. The reports continue to be rather favorable to the act of the Convention from every quarter','ltr_mad1581.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1582','letter','1787-10-24','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','You will herewith receive the result of the Convention, which continued its session till the 17th of September. I take the liberty of making some observ.ions on the subject, which will help to make up a letter, if they should answer no other purpose.','ltr_mad1582.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1583','letter','1787-10-28','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The remarks which you make on the act of the Convention appear to me to be in general extremely well founded.','ltr_mad1583.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1584','letter','1787-11-18','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','All my informations from RICHMOND concur in representing the enthusiasm in favor of the new Constitution as subsiding, and giving place to a spirit of criticism.','ltr_mad1584.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1585','letter','1787-11-20','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The latest authentic information from Europe places the Dutch in a wretched situation.','ltr_mad1585.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1586','letter','1787-12-07','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I understand that the Constitution will certainly be adopted in Connecticut, the returns of the Deputies being now known, and a very great majority found to be its declared and firm friends.','ltr_mad1586.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1587','letter','1787-12-09','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The annexed list of trees will shew you that I have ventured to substitute half a dozen sorts of apples in place of the pippins alone, and to add 8 other sorts of American Trees, including twenty of the Sugar maple.','ltr_mad1587.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1588','letter','1787-12-14','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I find by from RICHMOND that the proceedings of the Assembly are, as usual, rapidly degenerating with the progress of the Session; and particularly that the force opposed to the act of the Convention has gained the ascendance.','ltr_mad1588.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1589','letter','1787-12-26','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I am just informed by a Delegate from New Hampshire that he has a letter from President Sullivan, which tells him that the Legislature had unanimously agreed to call a Convention','ltr_mad1589.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1590','letter','1788-01-14','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The daily Advertiser this date contains several important articles of information, which need only to be referred to. I enclose it, with a few other late papers.','ltr_mad1590.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1591','letter','1788-01-20','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The Count de Moustier arrived here a few days ago, as successor to the Chevalier De La Luzerne.','ltr_mad1591.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1592','letter','1788-01-25','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','It is generally understood here that the arguments contained in it in favor of the Constitution are much stronger than the objections which prevented his assent.','ltr_mad1592.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1593','letter','1788-01-28','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The information which I have by the Eastern mail rather increases than removes the anxiety produced by the last. I give it to you as I have received it, in the words of Mr. King:','ltr_mad1593.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1594','letter','1788-02-01','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The eastern mail which arrived yesterday brought me a letter from Mr. King, of which a copy follows:','ltr_mad1594.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1595','letter','1788-02-08','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The form of the ratification of Georgia is contained in one of the papers herewith enclosed. Every information from South Carolina continues to be favorable.','ltr_mad1595.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1596','letter','1788-02-11','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The newspaper enclosed, with the letter which follows, comprises the information brought me by the mail of yesterday:','ltr_mad1596.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1597','letter','1788-02-15','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I have at length the pleasure to enclose you the favorable result of the Convention at Boston.','ltr_mad1597.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1598','letter','1788-02-19','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The public here continues to be much agitated by the proposed federal Constitution, and to be attentive to little else. At the date of my last, Delaware, Pennsylvania, and New Jersey, had adopted it.','ltr_mad1598.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1599','letter','1788-02-20','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I have given notice to my friends in Orange that the County may command my services in the Convention if it pleases.','ltr_mad1599.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1600','letter','1788-02-21','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','Your representation of the politics of the State coincides with the information from every other quarter. Great fluctuations and divisions of opinion naturally result in Virginia from the causes which you describe','ltr_mad1600.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1601','letter','1788-03-02','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The Convention of New Hampshire have disappointed much the general expectation. Instead of adopting the Constitution, they have adjourned, without any final decision','ltr_mad1601.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1602','letter','1788-03-03','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The Convention of New Hampshire has afforded a very disagreeable subject of communication. It has not rejected the Constitution, but it has failed to adopt it.','ltr_mad1602.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1603','letter','1788-04-10','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','Having seen a part only of the names returned for the Convention, and being unacquainted with the political characters of many of them, I am a very incompetent prophet of the fate of the Constitution.','ltr_mad1603.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1604','letter','1788-04-10','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','I view the amendments of Massachusetts pretty nearly in the same light that you do. They were meant for the people at large, not for the minority in the Convention.','ltr_mad1604.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1605','letter','1788-04-22','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The proposed Constitution still engrosses the public attention. The elections for the Convention here are but just over and promulged.','ltr_mad1605.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1606','letter','1788-06-04','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I found, contrary to my expectation, that not only a very full house had been made on the first day, but that it had proceeded to the appointment of the President and other officers.','ltr_mad1606.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1607','letter','1788-06-13','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','Appearances at present are less favorable than at the date of my last. Our progress is slow, and every advantage is taken of the delay to work on the local prejudices of particular sets of members.','ltr_mad1607.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1608','letter','1788-06-18','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','recipient_last','','No question, direct or indirect, has yet been taken by which the state of parties could be determined. Of course, each is left to enjoy the hopes resulting from its own partial calculations.','','description','ltr_mad1608.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1609','letter','1788-06-20','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Madison','Sr','individual','','No question has yet been taken by which the strength of parties can be determined.','ltr_mad1609.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1610','letter','1788-06-23','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','We got through the Constitution by paragraphs to-day. To-morrow, some proposition for closing the business will be made.','ltr_mad1610.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1611','letter','1788-06-25','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','On the question to-day for previous amendments, the votes stood 80 ayes, 88 noes.','ltr_mad1611.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1612','letter','1788-06-27','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The Convention came to a final adjournment today. The inclosed is a copy of their act of ratification, with the yeas and nays.','ltr_mad1612.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1613','letter','1788-07-21','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','Congress have deliberated in part on the arrangements for putting the new machine into operation, but have concluded on nothing but the times for choosing electors','ltr_mad1613.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1614','letter','1788-07-24','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I returned here about ten days ago from RICHMOND, which I left a day or two after the dissolution of the Convention. The final question on the new Government was put on the 25th of June.','ltr_mad1614.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1615','letter','1788-07-27','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Madison','Sr','individual','','After a very tedious discussion, the Constitution has been ratified by the Convention of this State.','ltr_mad1615.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1616','letter','1788-08-10','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','My last went off just as a vote was taken in the Convention of this State, which foretold the ratification of the new Government. The latter act soon followed, and is inclosed.','ltr_mad1616.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1617','letter','1788-08-15','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The place of meeting has undergone much discussion, as you conjectured, and still remains to be fixed. Philadelphia was first named, and negatived by a voice from Delaware.','ltr_mad1617.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1618','letter','1788-08-23','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The event, whatever may have been its cause, with the tendency of the circular letter from the Convention of New York, has somewhat changed the aspect of things','ltr_mad1618.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1619','letter','1788-08-24','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The circular letter from this State is certainly a matter of as much regret as the unanimity with which it passed is matter of surprize.','ltr_mad1619.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1620','letter','1788-09-06','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Madison','Sr','individual','','The anti-federalists are everywhere exerting themselves for an early Convention.','ltr_mad1620.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1621','letter','1788-09-14','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The delay in providing for the commencement of the Government was terminated yesterday, by an acquiescence of the minor number in the persevering demands of the major.','ltr_mad1621.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1622','letter','1788-09-21','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The circular letter from the New York Convention has rekindled an ardor among the opponents of the federal Constitution for an immediate revision of it by another General Convention.','ltr_mad1622.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1623','letter','1788-10-08','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','There is no doubt that General Washington will be called to the Presidency. For the vice Presidency are talked of principally Mr. Hancock and Mr. Adams.','ltr_mad1623.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1624','letter','1788-10-17','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The States which have adopted the New Constitution are all proceeding to the arrangements for putting it into action in March next.','ltr_mad1624.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1625','letter','1788-10-20','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The \"balmy\" nature of the Resolutions concerning the Mississippi will, I hope, have the effect you suggest','ltr_mad1625.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1626','letter','1788-10-21','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The Count Moustier and the Marchioness Brehan are to set out this day for Mount Vernon. I take it for granted you are not only apprised of the intended visit, but of the time at which the guests may be expected.','ltr_mad1626.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1627','letter','1788-11-02','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','G','Turberville','','individual','','You wish to know my sentiments on the project of another general Convention, as suggested by New York. I shall give them to you with great frankness','ltr_mad1627.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1628','letter','1788-11-05','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The enclosed memorandum was put into my hands by Mr. St. John, the French Consul. He is a very worthy man','ltr_mad1628.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1629','letter','1788-11-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','I am now pressed by some of my friends to repair to Virginia, as a requisite expedient for counteracting the machinations against my election into the House of Representatives.','ltr_mad1629.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1630','letter','1788-12-02','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I came to this city with a view either to return to New York or proceed to Virginia, as circumstances might require. I was not sure that the spirit of party might not take pleasure in superseding the opportunity of remaining longer in New York.','ltr_mad1630.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1631','letter','1788-12-08','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','This will be handed to you by Mr. Gouverneur Morris, who will embark in a few days for Havre, from whence he will proceed immediately to Paris. He is already well known to you by character','ltr_mad1631.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1632','letter','1788-12-10','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Philip','Mazzei','','individual','','Your book, as I prophesied, sells nowhere but in Virginia. A very few copies only have been called for either in New York or in this city. The language in which it is written will account for it.','ltr_mad1632.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1633','letter','1788-12-12','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','There will be seven representatives of the federal party, and one a moderate anti-federalist.','ltr_mad1633.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1634','letter','1789-01-02','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Eve','','individual','','Being informed that reports prevail not only that I am opposed to any amendments whatever to the new federal Constitution, but that I have ceased to be a friend to the rights of conscience...','ltr_mad1634.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1635','letter','1789-01-14','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I fear, from the vague accounts which circulate, that the federal Candidates are likely to stand in the way of each other.','ltr_mad1635.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1636','letter','1789-03-01','Alexandria','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','Your sanction to my remaining in New York during the crisis of the elections, conveyed through Col. Carrington, never came to hand till I had arrived in Orange.','ltr_mad1636.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1637','letter','1789-03-05','Baltimore','MD','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','On our Journey hither, we have fallen in with the bearer of the Electoral votes of Georgia. They are unanimous as to the President, and are all thrown away on Individuals of the State as to the Vice president.','ltr_mad1637.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1638','letter','1789-03-08','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I find that the communication made you from Kentucky corresponds with an official letter to Congress from Governor St. Clair, which speaks of the same emissary, and the same errand.','ltr_mad1638.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1639','letter','1789-03-19','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','When a quorum will be made up in either House rests on vague conjecture rather than on any precise information. It is not improbable, I think, that the present week will supply the deficiency in one, if not in both of them.','ltr_mad1639.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1640','letter','1789-03-26','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','It is the most authentic and precise evidence of the Spanish project that has come to my knowledge.','ltr_mad1640.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1641','letter','1789-03-29','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I was then on my way to Virginia. The elections for the new government commenced shortly after my arrival.','ltr_mad1641.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1642','letter','1789-04-06','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The arrival of R. H. Lee yesterday has made up a quorum of the Senate. A quorum in the other house was made on Wednesday last.','ltr_mad1642.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1643','letter','1789-04-08','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The first and only joint step taken by the Congress was the examination of the ballots for President and vice president. The votes were found, as was expected, to be unanimously given to General Washington','ltr_mad1643.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1644','letter','1789-04-12','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','I wish I could see an equal prospect of appeasing the disquietude on the two other points you mention British debts and taxes.','ltr_mad1644.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1645','letter','1789-04-19','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','We have not yet either the President or vice President on the ground. The former is expected in a few days. The latter, we are told, will certainly come in to-morrow evening.','ltr_mad1645.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1646','letter','1789-05-09','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The deliberations of the House of Representatives have been chiefly employed on the subject of an Impost. Opinions have been considerably divided on the quantum of duties that would be practicable','ltr_mad1646.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1647','letter','1789-05-10','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','The plan of an immediate temporary impost was what first occurred on the subject. It is not yet abandoned, but the practicability is questionable.','ltr_mad1647.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1648','letter','1789-05-13','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','The newspapers will have given you some idea of our proceedings, though in a state always mutilated, and often perverted. The impost is still the subject of deliberation.','ltr_mad1648.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1649','letter','1789-05-17','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edumund','Pendleton','','individual','','The. progress of our revenue system continues to be slow. The bill rating the duties is still with the Senate.','ltr_mad1649.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1650','letter','1789-05-23','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','My last inclosed copies of the President\'s inaugural Speech, and the answer of the House of Representatives. I now add the answer of the Senate.','ltr_mad1650.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1651','letter','1789-05-27','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','My former will have made known to you the obstacles to a licence for your visit to America. The new authority has not yet taken up your application.','ltr_mad1651.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1652','letter','1789-05-31','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','Our business here goes on very slowly, though in a spirit of moderation and accommodation which is so far flattering. The bill for regulating the quantum of duties is not yet come back from the Senate.','ltr_mad1652.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1653','letter','1789-06-17','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','A very interesting Question is started By whom officers appointed during pleasure by the President and Senate are to be displaced?','ltr_mad1653.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1654','letter','1789-06-21','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The Constitution has omitted to declare expressly by what authority removals from office are to be made. Out of this silence, four constructive doctrines have arisen:','ltr_mad1654.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1655','letter','1789-06-24','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','My last stated a question relating to the power of removal from offices then on the anvil of the House of Representatives.','ltr_mad1655.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1656','letter','1789-06-30','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','By this conveyance you will receive permission, through Mr. Jay, to make your proposed visit to America. I fear it will not reach you in time for your arrival here before the commencement of the windy season','ltr_mad1656.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1657','letter','1789-07-05','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Madison','Sr','individual','','The last letter from my brother A. left me in much anxiety for the state of my mother\'s health. I have ventured to hope, from the silence which has followed, that she has been on the recovery.','ltr_mad1657.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1658','letter','1789-07-15','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','It gives me much pleasure to find your approbation given to the decision of the House of Representatives on the power of removal. This appears to be the case with several of our friends in Virginia','ltr_mad1658.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1659','letter','1789-07-15','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','I am glad to find you concurring in the decision as to the power of removal. It seems to meet with general approbation North of Virginia, and there, too, as far as I yet learn.','ltr_mad1659.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1660','letter','1789-08-09','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','Your ideas on the proposed discrimination between foreign Nations coincide, I perceive, exactly with those which have governed me.','ltr_mad1660.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1661','letter','1789-08-21','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','For a week past the subject of amendments has exclusively occupied the House of Representatives. Its progress has been exceedingly wearisome','ltr_mad1661.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1662','letter','1789-09-14','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The Judiciary is now under consideration. I view it as you do, as defective both in its general structure, and many of its particular regulations.','ltr_mad1662.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1663','letter','1789-09-23','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The pressure of unfinished business has suspended the adjournment of Congress till Saturday next.','ltr_mad1663.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1664','letter','1789-11-20','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','A day or two after I got to Philadelphia I fell in with Mr. Morris. He broke the subject of the residence of Congress, and made observ.ions which betrayed his dislike of the upshot of the business at N. York','ltr_mad1664.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1665','letter','1789-12-05','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','Since my last I have been furnished with the inclosed copy of the letter from the Senators of this State to its Legislature. It is well calculated to keep alive the disaffection to the Government','ltr_mad1665.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1666','letter','1790-01-04','Georgetown','MD','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','After being detained 8 or ten days beyond the intended commencement of my journey by the critical illness of my mother, I am now subjected to a further delay by an attack on my own health','ltr_mad1666.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1667','letter','1790-01-24','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The business of Congress is as yet merely in embryo. The principal subjects before them are the plans of revenue and the Militia, reported by Hamilton and Knox.','ltr_mad1667.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1668','letter','1790-02-04','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The idea which the latter evolves is a great one, and suggests many interesting reflections to Legislators, particularly when contracting and providing for public debts.','ltr_mad1668.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1669','letter','1790-02-14','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','We proceed slowly in business. The Report of Mr. Hamilton has been, of late, the principal subject of debate. On the foreign debt the vote has been unanimous.','ltr_mad1669.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1670','letter','1790-03-04','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The only act of much consequence which the present Session has yet produced is one for enumerating the Inhabitants, as the basis of a reapportionment of the Representation.','ltr_mad1670.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1671','letter','1790-03-07','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Benjamin','Rush','','individual','','Although your last favor of the 27 February does not require any particular answer, I cannot let this occasional correspondence drop without thanking you for so interesting a supplement','ltr_mad1671.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1672','letter','1790-03-08','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The present subject of deliberation is the proposed assumption of the State debts. Opinions are nearly balanced on it.','ltr_mad1672.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1673','letter','1790-03-14','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The assumption of the State debts has of late employed most the House of Representatives. A majority of 5 agreed to the measure in Committee of the whole.','ltr_mad1673.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1674','letter','1790-03-21','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','I feel much anxiety for the situation in which you found Mrs. Randolph; but it is somewhat alleviated by the hopes which you seem to indulge.','ltr_mad1674.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1675','letter','1790-03-30','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','I have been so unlucky, also, as to miss seeing the President twice that I have waited on him, in order to intimate the circumstances which you wish him to know.','ltr_mad1675.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1676','letter','1790-04-04','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','You will see by the papers herewith covered that the proposed assumption of the State debts continues to employ the deliberations of the House of Representatives.','ltr_mad1676.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1677','letter','1790-04-13','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Heney','Lee','','individual','','In all these, I discover strong marks of the dissatisfaction with which you behold our public prospects. Though in several respects they do not comport with my wishes, yet I cannot feel all the despondency which you seem to give way to.','ltr_mad1677.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1678','letter','1790-04-13','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','I thank you for your favor of the 2nd instant. From the sentiments expressed in it, you will hear with pleasure that the proposed assumption of the State debts was yesterday negatived','ltr_mad1678.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1679','letter','1790-04-17','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','The House of Representatives are still at the threshold of the Revenue business. The assumption of the State debts is the great obstacle.','ltr_mad1679.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1680','letter','1790-05-02','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','I thank you very sincerely for the readiness with which you have complied with my troublesome request on the subject of the Stamp act.','ltr_mad1680.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1681','letter','1790-05-19','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The President has been critically ill for some days past, but is now, we hope, out of danger; his complaint is a peripneumony, united probably with the Influenza.','ltr_mad1681.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1682','letter','1790-06-01','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','The funding bill for the proper debt of the United States is engrossed for the last reading. It conforms in substance to the plan of the Secretary of the Treasury.','ltr_mad1682.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1683','letter','1790-06-17','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','The assumption still hangs over us. The negative of the measure has benumbed the whole revenue business. I suspect that it will yet be unavoidable to admit the evil in some qualified shape.','ltr_mad1683.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1684','letter','1790-06-22','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The funding and Revenue systems are reduced by the discord of opinions into a very critical state. Out of this extremity, however, some effective provision must, I think, still emerge.','ltr_mad1684.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1685','letter','1790-07-04','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','You will find by one of the Gazettes herewith sent, that the bill fixing the permanent seat of Government on the Potowmac, and the temporary at Philadelphia, has got through the Senate.','ltr_mad1685.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1686','letter','1790-07-24','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','After all the vicissitudes through which the assumption has passed, it seems at present in a fair way to succeed as part of the general plan for the public debt.','ltr_mad1686.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1689','letter','1791-02-13','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The power of incorporating cannot, by any process of safe reasoning, be drawn within the meaning of the Constitution as an appurtenance of any express power, and it is not pretended that it is itself an express power.','ltr_mad1689.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1690','letter','1791-02-13','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Madison','Sr','individual','','am glad to find that my sister Hite has withdrawn herself from the region of the small-pox. It gives me particular pleasure, also, to learn that my mother\'s health has been so far restored.','ltr_mad1690.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1691','letter','1791-05-01','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','From conversations which I have casually heard, it appears that among the enormities produced by the spirit of speculation and fraud, a practice is spreading of taking out administration on the effects of deceased soldiers and other claimants leaving no representatives.','ltr_mad1691.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1692','letter','1791-05-12','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I had seen Paine\'s pamphlet, with the preface of the Philadelphia Editor. It immediately occured that you were brought into the Frontispiece in the manner you explain.','ltr_mad1692.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1693','letter','1791-06-27','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','Mr. Adams seems to be getting faster and faster into difficulties. His attack on Paine, which I have not seen, will draw the public attention to his obnoxious principles more than everything he has published.','ltr_mad1693.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1694','letter','1791-07-10','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The Bank shares have risen as much in the Market here as at Philadelphia. It seems admitted on all hands now that the plan of the institution gives a moral certainty of gain to the subscribers','ltr_mad1694.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1695','letter','1791-07-13','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','Beckley has just got back from his eastern trip. He says that the partizans of Mr. Adams\'s heresies in that quarter are perfectly insignificant in point of number; that particularly in Boston he is become distinguished for his unpopularity','ltr_mad1695.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1696','letter','1791-08-04','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','Stock and scrip continue to be the sole domestic subjects of conversation.','ltr_mad1696.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1697','letter','1791-08-08','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','It is surmised that the deferred debt is to be taken up at the next session, and some anticipated provision made for it.','ltr_mad1697.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1698','letter','1791-10-30','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Egbert','Pleasants','','individual','','The petition relating to the Militia bill contains nothing that makes it improper for me to present it. I shall, therefore, readily comply with your desire on that subject.','ltr_mad1698.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1699','letter','1791-00-00','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Heney','Lee','','individual','','I regret that I can administer no balm to the wound given by the first report of our Western disaster. You will have seen the official account which has gone into all the Newspapers.','ltr_mad1699.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1700','letter','1791-12-18','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The two Houses have been of late chiefly occupied by the Representation bill, which, both in its principles and consequences, is of the first importance.','ltr_mad1700.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1701','letter','1792-01-22','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','recipient_last','','individual','','I have delayed for some time writing, in the daily expectation that I should be able to resume the subject of the Representation bill, the progress and fate of which were mentioned in my last.','ltr_mad1701.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1702','letter','1792-01-29','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Heney','Lee','','individual','','The subject of Western defence is not yet over. In relation to it I have nothing to add to the communications in my last.','ltr_mad1702.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1703','letter','1792-02-12','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Heney','Lee','','individual','','The Senate have disagreed to that part of the Military Bill which augmented the regular establishment to about 5,000 men, and will probably send it back with that alteration.','ltr_mad1703.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1704','letter','1792-02-21','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','The Bill concerning the election of a President and vice President, and the eventual successor to both, which has long been depending, has finally got through the two Houses.','ltr_mad1704.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1705','letter','1792-03-25','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','You were right in saying \"that the Northern Cocks are true game,\"but have erred in adding, \"that they die hard on the Representation bill.\" Their perseverance has gained them a final victory.','ltr_mad1705.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1706','letter','1792-03-28','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Heney','Lee','','individual','','No nomination has yet been made of a new Commander for the Military establishment, nor of any of the Brigadiers authorized by the supplemental act lately passed.','ltr_mad1706.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1707','letter','1792-04-09','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','You will find by the inclosed papers that the President\'s negative has saved us from the unconstitutional allotment of 120 Representatives proposed by the Bill on that subject.','ltr_mad1707.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1708','letter','1792-04-15','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Heney','Lee','','individual','','You know already that the President has exerted his power of checking the unconstitutional career of Congress.','ltr_mad1708.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1709','letter','1792-06-12','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I have from Kentucky down to the 8th May. Little depredations from the savages continue to be complained of. The people, however, are chiefly occupied with the approaching distribution of the new offices.','ltr_mad1709.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1710','letter','1792-06-21','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','The questions which it presents for consideration are 1st . At what time a notification of your purpose to retire will be most convenient?','ltr_mad1710.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1711','letter','1792-09-13','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Randolph','','individual','','That I wished and recommended Mr. Freneau to be appointed to his present Clerkship is certain. But the Department of State was not the only, nor, as I recollect, the first one, to which I mentioned his name and character.','ltr_mad1711.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1712','letter','1792-11-16','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','You will find in them all the particulars known here concerning the affairs of France, and sketches of the business as yet brought before Congress.','ltr_mad1712.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1713','letter','1792-12-06','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','It appears, on the whole, that the combination against the revolution, and particularly against their new Republic, is extremely formidable, and that there is still greater danger within from the follies and barbarities which prevail in Paris.','ltr_mad1713.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1714','letter','1792-12-10','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','As you find an amusement in our newspapers, I inclose two of the last; which, however, contain little of consequence, except a new Report from the Treasury Department.','ltr_mad1714.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1715','letter','1793-02-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Edmund','Pendleton','','individual','','Since we had the pleasure of Col. Taylor\'s arrival, I have left in his better hands the trust of keeping you supplied with whatever communications might interest or amuse you.','ltr_mad1715.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1716','letter','1793-04-12','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The refusal of Dunlap in the case you mention confirms the idea of a combined influence against the freedom of the press.','ltr_mad1716.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1717','letter','1793-05-08','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I anxiously wish that the reception of Genet may testify what I believe to be the real affections of the people. It is the more desirable, as a seasonable plum after the bitter pills which it seems must be administered.','ltr_mad1717.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1718','letter','1793-05-27','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I feel for your situation, but you must bear it. Every consideration, private as well as public, requires a further sacrifice of your longings for the repose of Monticello.','ltr_mad1718.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1719','letter','1793-06-13','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I observ. that the newspapers continue to criticise the President\'s proclamation, and I find that some of the criticisms excite the attention of dispassionate and judicious individuals here.','ltr_mad1719.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1720','letter','1793-06-17','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I fell in two days ago with French Strother, who was returning circuitously from RICHMOND. He had seen W. C. Nicholas on his way, and spoke of him as among the decided friends of the French cause.','ltr_mad1720.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1721','letter','1793-06-19','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','It is mortifying to the real friends of the President that his fame and his influence should have been unnecessarily made to depend in any degree on political events in a foreign quarter of the Globe','ltr_mad1721.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1722','letter','1793-06-29','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','Much will depend on events in Europe; and it is to be regretted that the popularity of the President or the policy of our Government should ever be staked on such contingencies.','ltr_mad1722.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1723','letter','1793-07-18','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I have read over the subject which you recommend to my attention. It excites equally surprise and indignation, and ought certainly to be taken notice of by some one who can do it justice.','ltr_mad1723.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1724','letter','1793-07-22','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','From his conversation, his sentiments are right and firm on the French Revolution, and in other respects I discovered no symptoms of heresy.','ltr_mad1724.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1725','letter','1793-07-30','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','Do you know what is the idea of France with regard to the defensive quality of the guaranty, and of the criterion between offensive and defensive war, which I find differently defined by different jurists; also, what are the ideas of the President on these points?','ltr_mad1725.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1726','letter','1793-08-05','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','Your account of the ticklish situation with respect to Genet in the 14 th is truly distressing. His folly would almost beget suspicions of the worst sort.','ltr_mad1726.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1727','letter','1793-08-11','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The task on which you have put me must be abridged, so as not to go beyond that period. You will see that the first topic is not yet completed.','ltr_mad1727.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1728','letter','1793-08-20','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I am just setting off to Monroe\'s, and hope to prevent the trouble of an express from Monticello with the letter referred to in it. I have already acquainted you with the immediate object of this visit.','ltr_mad1728.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1729','letter','1793-08-22','At Col. Monroes','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The whole piece was more hurried than it ought to have been, and these paragraphs penned in the instant of my setting out, which had been delayed as late as would leave enough of the day for the journey.','ltr_mad1729.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1730','letter','1793-08-27','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','I have since seen the RICHMOND and the Philad\'a papers, containing, the latter, the certificate of Jay & King, and the publications relating to the subject of it; the former, the proceedings at RICHMOND, dictated, no doubt, by the cabal at Philad\'a','ltr_mad1730.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1731','letter','1793-09-02','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','Thomas','Jefferson','','individual','','The conduct of Genet, as developed in these, and in his proceedings as exhibited in the newspapers, is as unaccountable as it is distressing. The effect is beginning to be strongly felt here','ltr_mad1731.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1732','letter','1793-09-15','','','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','Since I parted from you I have had several letters from Mr. Jefferson, in which all the facts involving Genet are detailed. His conduct has been that of a madman.','ltr_mad1732.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1733','letter','1793-10-24','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','George','Washington','','individual','','I now lose not a moment in complying with its request; tho\' I foresee it cannot reach you before you will have left Mount Vernon','ltr_mad1733.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1734','letter','1793-10-29','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','Jr','James','Monroe','','individual','','I send the little balance of tea due to Mrs. Monroe, which I intended, but failed, to procure before my late trip.','ltr_mad1734.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
